1
00:00:10,071 --> 00:00:11,474
Greetings, good evening.

2
00:00:12,314 --> 00:00:14,837
I hope you've, I trust you've had a fruitful day.

3
00:00:14,878 --> 00:00:18,661
I do not say happy, although I wish it had been happy for you.

4
00:00:20,344 --> 00:00:36,703
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa

5
00:00:37,426 --> 00:00:53,548
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Samma Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble and Self-Awakened One.

6
00:00:53,969 --> 00:00:58,094
This evening, I just want to start with a practical question that's come through.

7
00:00:59,655 --> 00:01:04,462
It's from Danny.

8
00:01:05,152 --> 00:01:08,256
I have a technical job assembling electromechanical units.

9
00:01:08,296 --> 00:01:13,061
This involves reading a drawing, collating the parts, and getting the parts to fit together.

10
00:01:14,043 --> 00:01:21,552
I try to maintain a degree of mindfulness, but with all the movements associated with these activities, it becomes exhausting.

11
00:01:21,751 --> 00:01:29,120
Instead, I note walking from A to B and standing, but I spend more time at the bench.

12
00:01:30,341 --> 00:01:33,605
I have tried to note looking and seeing during these times,

13
00:01:33,923 --> 00:01:41,391
And even with this, I'm aware of other actions too, and then note that I'm ignoring these objects to force my attention on the seeing.

14
00:01:42,253 --> 00:01:45,275
This can be followed by frustration, again, noted.

15
00:01:46,477 --> 00:01:57,650
My formal practice is one of slow noting, even though, for example, when I raise my heel, I'm aware of the other touch sensations, but do not note them as independent sensations.

16
00:01:59,212 --> 00:02:02,596
My question then is, how to maintain mindfulness at work

17
00:02:02,915 --> 00:02:07,260
When I'm involved in an activity, that needs to be done with relative speed.

18
00:02:09,622 --> 00:02:17,110
Now, this is, by the way, a regular sort of question that comes from people who practice the Mahasi technique.

19
00:02:17,771 --> 00:02:26,461
The Mahasi technique is a very specific technique for a particular type of situation, the retreat.

20
00:02:27,502 --> 00:02:30,846
And the whole idea, of course, is to slow everything down.

21
00:02:31,568 --> 00:02:36,614
And the noting is a way of stopping the mind from wandering.

22
00:02:37,074 --> 00:02:42,100
It has this other purpose, which is to turn everything into an object.

23
00:02:42,301 --> 00:02:44,223
You're pointing at something all the time.

24
00:02:45,224 --> 00:03:00,764
But in terms of this question, it's the retreat or the Mahasi technique is about slowing everything down and noting, especially intentions, and becoming more and more refined in order to see how the mind is creating the world

25
00:03:01,082 --> 00:03:02,245
that we're experiencing.

26
00:03:03,225 --> 00:03:22,955
Now, when you go out into daily life, I was, uh, I didn't, I didn't have trouble, uh, this sort of trouble because I had started with Zen and, uh, I practiced up at Thrustle Hole, um, in Northumberland and, um, yeah, Northumberland, yeah, uh, turned left at Newcastle.

27
00:03:23,877 --> 00:03:27,562
And, um, there we did things at speed.

28
00:03:27,842 --> 00:03:28,905
I mean, really fast.

29
00:03:29,626 --> 00:03:30,347
And, um,

30
00:03:31,306 --> 00:03:34,991
for long times, an hour, two hours even sometimes.

31
00:03:35,692 --> 00:03:43,602
And I remember one time, for instance, I was given the job of the dining room, and part of it was polishing the chairs.

32
00:03:44,282 --> 00:03:48,608
And I had to polish the chairs as if they'd never been polished.

33
00:03:50,009 --> 00:03:52,073
And you did it at great speed.

34
00:03:52,652 --> 00:03:57,759
And the understanding is, of course, is that the faster you go, the more you've got to keep your mindfulness.

35
00:03:57,900 --> 00:03:59,322
Your attention is right there.

36
00:03:59,587 --> 00:04:05,575
If your attention wanders, then you'll drop something, you'll trip up, you'll make a mistake.

37
00:04:06,858 --> 00:04:11,865
It's not as though mindfulness stops you making mistakes as such because accidents happen.

38
00:04:13,668 --> 00:04:20,456
So I never had this problem of transferring noting into daily life because, frankly, I never did it.

39
00:04:21,759 --> 00:04:29,410
It was, it didn't see, because of my Zen training, I knew that what I had to do was just, you know, put my attention on what I was doing.

40
00:04:30,048 --> 00:04:50,528
Now, when you are doing something, especially something that demands attention, I mean, careful attention, such as the work that Danny does, then, of course, noting can get in the way because your whole attention is towards the object.

41
00:04:51,209 --> 00:04:58,317
Now, those of you who've been here know that when I talk about meditation at work,

42
00:04:59,528 --> 00:05:07,454
doing the chores in the morning, then yes, the idea is to be with what you're doing.

43
00:05:07,855 --> 00:05:16,141
And sometimes there's a sort of a confusion about self-awareness, that you have to be aware of yourself all the time doing something.

44
00:05:16,723 --> 00:05:23,247
But that's, of course, a split consciousness in the sense that one minute you're aware of yourself and one minute you're aware of what you're doing.

45
00:05:23,908 --> 00:05:26,670
So that's not where we want to end up.

46
00:05:26,730 --> 00:05:29,112
Self-awareness arises quite naturally.

47
00:05:29,649 --> 00:05:32,031
And you can't get rid of it by creating another self.

48
00:05:32,372 --> 00:05:35,055
It just creates confusion.

49
00:05:36,437 --> 00:05:41,562
But as you keep paying attention to what you're doing, then there's moments of absorption.

50
00:05:42,442 --> 00:05:47,668
Now, this happens to us quite easily when we're watching something exciting like a film.

51
00:05:47,687 --> 00:05:49,189
You absorb into the film.

52
00:05:49,569 --> 00:05:51,271
You know, you disappear for a couple of hours.

53
00:05:51,891 --> 00:05:53,574
And when you come out, you say, oh, that's a good film.

54
00:05:54,295 --> 00:05:55,435
And it's the same with hobbies.

55
00:05:56,036 --> 00:05:59,639
When we're really interested in what we're doing, gardening or something, time can just

56
00:05:59,975 --> 00:06:29,711
fly by and that's and that's when we lose that sense of self somebody doing something and with it of course a sense of time it always happens to the computer a lot you know and other other other ways like facebook and all that so when we're at work our effort of course is to be attentive to what we're doing now it might be that some noting helps us just to pay attention to that but

57
00:06:29,978 --> 00:06:32,160
In a sense, we don't want it to get in the way.

58
00:06:32,420 --> 00:06:36,983
We want to pay attention to such a point that I'm just being my doing.

59
00:06:37,024 --> 00:06:39,526
That's the trick of it, you see.

60
00:06:40,286 --> 00:06:46,392
So it's not a case of being self-aware of what you're doing.

61
00:06:46,913 --> 00:06:51,336
It's not a case of being aware of everything else around what you're doing.

62
00:06:51,538 --> 00:06:57,622
It's a case of one-pointed concentration work that you're supposed to be attending to.

63
00:06:58,413 --> 00:07:03,341
So it's not a case of noting everything specifically.

64
00:07:05,223 --> 00:07:06,586
And at times you can just drop that.

65
00:07:06,846 --> 00:07:14,317
When you know that your attention is steady, when you can trust it to remain with what you're doing, then you've arrived.

66
00:07:14,338 --> 00:07:14,718
That's it.

67
00:07:15,500 --> 00:07:25,415
Now, when you go into an absorption where you lose that sense of self and you're just doing, of course, how you enter into it

68
00:07:25,970 --> 00:07:29,494
is the state of the mental state that you'll be developing.

69
00:07:29,994 --> 00:07:41,404
So if you go into it, uh, with a calmness, a sense of, you know, uh, just doing a sense of equanimity or whatever, or even a sense of, um, uh, kindness.

70
00:07:41,745 --> 00:07:51,295
I mean, that's more easy with, with, if you're tending to people rather than, uh, than a machine and stuff, or with a machine, it'd be more carefulness to be care, caring.

71
00:07:51,956 --> 00:07:53,918
So it's, it's, um,

72
00:07:54,151 --> 00:08:00,877
It makes everything easy if you can bring your heart into it, give it a good reason for doing what you're doing.

73
00:08:02,779 --> 00:08:15,572
And if you go into it with care and attention, affectionate awareness, excuse me, then you come out with more of that because you're developing it.

74
00:08:16,353 --> 00:08:23,600
If you go in there with a sense of rush, then, of course, you're reinforcing that attitude and you come out with more rush.

75
00:08:23,935 --> 00:08:27,420
And that can lead to an early exhaustion.

76
00:08:28,401 --> 00:08:38,315
So I'm presuming that what Danny's saying here is that trying to note and do the work, he's found exhausting, and rightly so.

77
00:08:38,855 --> 00:08:42,480
So the thing to do is to do the work.

78
00:08:42,559 --> 00:08:48,989
If the mind's very jittery, it's going all over the place, then yes, keep noting a little bit just to put your attention there.

79
00:08:49,009 --> 00:08:52,474
But as soon as you feel that you're holding your attention,

80
00:08:52,740 --> 00:08:57,187
and that you're involved and let go of it, right?

81
00:08:57,307 --> 00:08:58,707
Just be aware, it's enough.

82
00:09:00,490 --> 00:09:05,096
So now if that didn't answer the question, especially Dan, if you didn't answer the question, just send me another email.

83
00:09:06,538 --> 00:09:15,269
And yeah, do feel free to send questions about your meditation practice and so on.

84
00:09:15,288 --> 00:09:15,730
Very good.

85
00:09:16,370 --> 00:09:17,652
So I'm finally...

86
00:09:18,830 --> 00:09:24,937
Arriving at the question, are all the stages of the Eightfold Path equally important?

87
00:09:27,220 --> 00:09:32,605
Now, the short answer is yes, but some precede the others.

88
00:09:33,105 --> 00:09:36,769
So they have preference in sense of preceding the others.

89
00:09:36,850 --> 00:09:41,134
But eventually they're all important in our practice.

90
00:09:42,197 --> 00:09:43,538
And so...

91
00:09:43,837 --> 00:09:51,145
The first thing is to be clear as to what the Eightfold Path is actually referring to here.

92
00:09:51,787 --> 00:10:01,557
So remember, we've got right view, right understanding, which is followed by right attitude, right intention.

93
00:10:02,238 --> 00:10:06,042
And then you have right speech, you have right action, right livelihood.

94
00:10:06,361 --> 00:10:07,003
It's interesting.

95
00:10:07,823 --> 00:10:13,389
And then you have right concentration, right awareness and right effort, right action.

96
00:10:13,589 --> 00:10:15,230
awareness, right concentration.

97
00:10:16,953 --> 00:10:28,150
Now, interestingly enough, when you actually talk about this as a practice, you start off with SILA, you start off with morality, which is right speech, right action, right livelihood.

98
00:10:28,691 --> 00:10:30,333
And then you talk about the meditation.

99
00:10:30,354 --> 00:10:35,721
And then finally, you talk about the wisdom, the right view and right attitude.

100
00:10:36,984 --> 00:10:38,466
But when you're actually

101
00:10:38,833 --> 00:10:50,509
talking about it as a logical process, as to how it actually knits all together, then you talk about it in this eightfold way.

102
00:10:52,371 --> 00:11:03,807
So I'm going to follow just the eightfold path, not the teaching way of sila samadhi panya, which is morality, concentration or attentiveness, and wisdom.

103
00:11:05,708 --> 00:11:08,773
So when the Buddha talks about samadhiti,

104
00:11:09,208 --> 00:11:20,246
right view, right awareness, he's basically referring to the Four Noble Truths as the basic, as the base of our understanding.

105
00:11:21,327 --> 00:11:26,255
And from a practical point of view, from our practice point of view, in terms of Vipassana,

106
00:11:26,539 --> 00:11:40,217
It really is relating to those three characteristics of existence, that the cause of suffering is desire, that everything changes, nothing actually changes into something else.

107
00:11:40,298 --> 00:11:48,690
Everything is quite spare, quite distinct, and there's this constant impermanence going on, and that everything is not self.

108
00:11:48,710 --> 00:11:52,215
From a human point of view, everything is not self.

109
00:11:52,695 --> 00:11:56,259
Everything isn't substantial.

110
00:11:56,711 --> 00:11:59,294
Nothing can exist on its own.

111
00:11:59,335 --> 00:12:03,798
It's always in relationship, in dependency on something.

112
00:12:04,159 --> 00:12:07,842
So obviously the body's dependent on the air that we breathe and so on.

113
00:12:09,465 --> 00:12:13,708
And the heart dependent on relationships and the mind dependent on information.

114
00:12:14,210 --> 00:12:16,392
So everything has something to feed.

115
00:12:16,792 --> 00:12:17,913
It's got to be fed.

116
00:12:17,974 --> 00:12:19,394
It's got to be related to.

117
00:12:22,018 --> 00:12:26,381
But the interesting thing is this Samaditti, this Sam right view,

118
00:12:26,631 --> 00:12:28,934
is really about conceptual thinking.

119
00:12:30,756 --> 00:12:43,754
And if you think about it, everything that we experience during the day, everything we look at, we hear, et cetera, et cetera, it's always fitting it into a particular concept.

120
00:12:46,076 --> 00:12:49,481
This process actually has a word in psychology, apperception.

121
00:12:50,062 --> 00:12:54,447
So you see something and you've not seen it before.

122
00:12:54,467 --> 00:12:56,571
And when you look at it closely,

123
00:12:56,821 --> 00:13:01,567
and get closer, oh, yeah, well, that must be a type of fly, yeah?

124
00:13:01,586 --> 00:13:06,333
Or if you taste something which you haven't tasted before, it's, oh, well, this must be a type of Chinese dish.

125
00:13:07,134 --> 00:13:16,226
So you're always fitting it in to your preconceived concepts, your preconceived ideas, which have been built up ever since we were born.

126
00:13:17,288 --> 00:13:20,533
And a lot of them are sort of,

127
00:13:20,934 --> 00:13:29,243
subconscious, we're not fully aware of these concepts that we are always looking at the world through.

128
00:13:29,302 --> 00:13:35,548
The obvious ones, things like freedom.

129
00:13:35,789 --> 00:13:38,131
Now, you know, what do we mean by freedom?

130
00:13:40,173 --> 00:13:50,283
And this idea, I remember a few years ago now, there was this whole thing about the right to insult, which is a very sort of aggressive way of saying

131
00:13:50,585 --> 00:14:02,783
Now, you know, you can say things which might upset others, but the way it came across was that you had to go and punch somebody with your new ideas or with your view.

132
00:14:04,446 --> 00:14:17,384
So this whole idea of free speech, the whole idea of personal liberty, the whole idea of democracy, parliamentary democracy, all these are great big concepts which...

133
00:14:17,652 --> 00:14:21,135
manifest our relationship to the world we find ourselves in.

134
00:14:21,596 --> 00:14:27,063
And there's the negative ones, there's all the prejudices, sexism, racism, ageism.

135
00:14:27,183 --> 00:14:29,886
Now I'm very much aware of ageism these days.

136
00:14:30,668 --> 00:14:38,638
So you can see the way we look at the world is always coming from some preconceived ideas.

137
00:14:40,159 --> 00:14:45,886
And what the Buddha says is that unless we can really correct these ideas, unless we can correct this

138
00:14:46,171 --> 00:14:53,519
these perceptions, these conceptions, then we're just not going to get out of the mess we're in.

139
00:14:54,321 --> 00:15:03,731
And that's why he's always keen to deconstruct what we experience and to begin to investigate what we experience.

140
00:15:03,751 --> 00:15:15,485
So the main one is, of course, the one that we, shall we say, directly experience virtually all the time is this relationship we have to pleasure and pain, pleasant and unpleasant.

141
00:15:16,140 --> 00:15:26,836
And what he's saying is, if you remember from the beginning of the discourse last night, it's neither indulging nor is it being averse to something.

142
00:15:26,875 --> 00:15:38,091
So we're trying to lift ourselves out of this reactivity, right, which comes from a fundamental misunderstanding somewhere as to where we can find happiness.

143
00:15:38,951 --> 00:15:40,934
Yeah, that's where the base of it is.

144
00:15:41,034 --> 00:15:42,317
We all want to be happy.

145
00:15:42,787 --> 00:15:44,188
We're all chasing happiness.

146
00:15:44,208 --> 00:15:46,532
We've all got our own definition of happiness.

147
00:15:47,153 --> 00:15:53,140
And it's all coming from this wrong understanding as to where we can find true happiness.

148
00:15:53,761 --> 00:15:54,241
Yeah.

149
00:15:54,261 --> 00:15:57,265
Or true well-being or true ease with living.

150
00:15:58,408 --> 00:16:03,193
An accommodation with life, which no longer is painful for us.

151
00:16:04,615 --> 00:16:07,359
So Samaditi is that.

152
00:16:08,561 --> 00:16:11,544
And included in that would be the very

153
00:16:11,794 --> 00:16:33,735
um important teaching about karma the fact that uh when we act there are consequences that's a a real experience a real understanding i mean there were teachers at the time um of the buddha who said that there was no there was one especially the lati puta i think his name was um

154
00:16:34,001 --> 00:16:44,433
who said it didn't matter if you went down one side of the Ganges, full of compassionate act and generosity, and at the other side full of murder and thieving, it wouldn't make a difference at all.

155
00:16:44,754 --> 00:16:45,816
It had no consequence.

156
00:16:46,336 --> 00:17:03,216
So there was all these peculiar ideas going around at the time, and the Buddha was clear about action and consequence of action, and that the action had to have some awareness of what you were doing,

157
00:17:03,820 --> 00:17:10,752
So killing something by accident or, you know, the usual thing of, say, sometimes here.

158
00:17:11,253 --> 00:17:19,911
I've not done it so much here, but at Gaia House, I remember when I was there, I'd be walking in the dark and I could hear this crunch and it'd be a snail I just stood on, you know.

159
00:17:21,133 --> 00:17:24,759
And obviously I didn't mean to do it.

160
00:17:25,059 --> 00:17:26,502
You know, I've got that.

161
00:17:26,752 --> 00:17:29,075
It's a natural regard for snails.

162
00:17:29,976 --> 00:17:38,063
And that wouldn't be considered to have bad karma, except that, of course, one feels guilty anyway, one feels bad anyway.

163
00:17:38,144 --> 00:17:42,407
But that's not necessary because there wasn't the intention there.

164
00:17:42,428 --> 00:17:48,292
So the whole teaching about karma, it comes into this right understanding.

165
00:17:49,933 --> 00:17:55,900
Now, when we've got this right understanding, as I say, that comes first.

166
00:17:56,166 --> 00:18:04,099
And it begins with what we hear, what we're told, what we receive.

167
00:18:04,761 --> 00:18:12,153
And then, as it were, it becomes our own personal knowledge, our own personal understanding when we think about it.

168
00:18:12,815 --> 00:18:20,367
Often, I'm sure you've found that you've understood something, but when you've tried to explain it to somebody else, you can't do it.

169
00:18:21,174 --> 00:18:25,400
And so that's the same with this growth of understanding.

170
00:18:25,440 --> 00:18:34,271
The first is through your reading, through your listening, et cetera, information comes in, and then somehow you've got to sort of think about it.

171
00:18:34,491 --> 00:18:39,778
You've got to activate it within yourself, and then it becomes your own property.

172
00:18:40,559 --> 00:18:51,012
And then, of course, it has to be reinforced by direct experience, and that's vipassana, vipassana jnana, knowing by way of direct experience.

173
00:18:51,871 --> 00:18:56,757
And that's when it becomes your own personal experience.

174
00:18:56,777 --> 00:19:02,864
And then you find it has this flowing through the rest of the path.

175
00:19:03,364 --> 00:19:07,229
And the next thing, of course, is that it changes your attitude.

176
00:19:07,890 --> 00:19:09,310
It changes what you intend.

177
00:19:10,192 --> 00:19:15,638
Some people translate it as thought, which I can understand, but I don't think it's quite right.

178
00:19:15,659 --> 00:19:19,363
I don't quite get across the meaning of sama samanta.

179
00:19:21,840 --> 00:19:23,001
Samasankapa, excuse me.

180
00:19:24,383 --> 00:19:32,771
Because when that's described, it's described as moving away from greed and selfishness towards generosity.

181
00:19:33,172 --> 00:19:37,556
And it's a process of renunciation, renouncing that wrong desire.

182
00:19:38,136 --> 00:19:41,480
So moving from greed towards generosity.

183
00:19:41,859 --> 00:19:47,326
It's described as moving towards hatred and aversion towards love and acceptance.

184
00:19:47,945 --> 00:19:50,868
And it's described as moving away from harmfulness

185
00:19:51,170 --> 00:19:56,017
from cruelty, from one-upmanship and all that sort of stuff towards compassion.

186
00:19:56,538 --> 00:19:58,760
So these are attitudes.

187
00:19:59,181 --> 00:20:06,050
And it's out of these attitudes that these intentions begin to manifest in a given circumstance.

188
00:20:06,912 --> 00:20:12,118
And from then, of course, you're into right thinking in your mind, which is a sort of speech.

189
00:20:12,239 --> 00:20:13,421
I mean, you're talking to yourself.

190
00:20:13,922 --> 00:20:17,527
Then it goes into right speech, right action, right livelihood.

191
00:20:18,228 --> 00:20:19,809
And all this is supported by

192
00:20:20,109 --> 00:20:21,674
by your meditation.

193
00:20:23,038 --> 00:20:23,358
Okay.

194
00:20:23,800 --> 00:20:33,528
And we'll say a bit more about the right speech, right action and all that, and especially right livelihood, actually, tomorrow evening.

195
00:20:36,444 --> 00:20:47,896
So that's the short answer is that all these sections in the Eightfold Path are equally important, but that some precede another, right?

196
00:20:47,977 --> 00:20:50,720
And of course, right understanding precedes them all.

197
00:20:51,181 --> 00:20:57,988
It then has the effect upon your attitudes and then the rest flows naturally depending on the circumstance.

198
00:20:58,067 --> 00:21:02,092
So sometimes you're talking, sometimes you're doing something, sometimes you're at work.

199
00:21:02,732 --> 00:21:02,992
Okay.

200
00:21:06,532 --> 00:21:11,564
So if any questions arise about that, you know, do send me an email.

201
00:21:12,146 --> 00:21:15,446
So I shall leave it there for this evening so that we can get back.

